        "materials_required": [
            "Quikcrete (or other PlaySand)",
            "Box Created for Castings",
            "Razor Blade",
            "Salt (Sea salt seemed to work best)",
            "Hairspray (high strength hold)"
        ],
        "description": "This project details the process of solidifying sand into a desired geometry using either salt water or hairspray as bonding agents. It's designed as the first part of a series exploring minimal surfaces created with sand.",
        "steps": [
            "Create your desired geometry within the casting box using dry sand. For saltwater solidification, mix 10 parts sand with 1 part salt.",
            "Prepare your solidifying agent: For saltwater, dissolve 3 tablespoons of sea salt in 2 cups of warm water and pour into a spray bottle. For hairspray, ensure you have a bottle with a high-strength hold.",
            "Spray the geometry completely with the chosen agent (saltwater or hairspray). Apply several light coats, avoiding oversaturation. Use a heat source like a light or heat gun to speed up drying if needed.",
            "Carefully remove the sides of the box, using a razor blade to cut along the edges if necessary. Slowly remove the loose sand from the underside of the hardened shell.",
            "Once removed, clean any loose sand from the bottom of the shell and spray with hairspray for extra strength."
        ]
